{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537998"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:23:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:23:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16097"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16097"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.05,0.01,0.82,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64803"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8788"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50237"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1636"},{"type":"tags","id":"1652"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4135"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20983"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43605"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64803"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents at 12 weeks gestation with vaginal bleeding and severe morning sickness. Her uterus is larger than expected for dates. Ultrasound scan shows a \u0027snowstorm\u0027 appearance with multiple vesicular structures throughout the uterine cavity, and no visible fetus. Her human chorionic gonadotropin level is 250,000 IU/L (50-10,000). She has bilateral theca lutein cysts measuring 8 cm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer vital signs are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood pressure: 160/95 mmHg\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHeart rate: 105 beats/minute\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERespiratory rate: 20 breaths/minute\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETemperature: 37.2\u00b0C\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most concerning long term risk for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endometrial carcinoma","Ovarian carcinoma","Cervical carcinoma","Choriocarcinoma","Vaginal carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a clinical picture consistent with a complete molar pregnancy and has multiple high-risk features for developing persistent gestational trophoblastic disease, particularly \u003Cstrong\u003Echoriocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. These features include markedly elevated human chorionic gonadotropin (250,000 IU/L), large bilateral theca lutein cysts, and medical complications (hypertension).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile gynaecologic cancers including \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eovarian carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Evaginal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in women of reproductive age, they are not specifically associated with molar pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for persistent gestational trophoblastic disease after molar pregnancy include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHuman chorionic gonadotropin \u0026gt;100,000 IU/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELarge theca lutein cysts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical complications (hypertension, hyperthyroidism)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUterine size larger than dates\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevious molar pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApproximately 15-20% of complete molar pregnancies will develop persistent disease, with choriocarcinoma being the most aggressive form. This highlights the importance of careful post-evacuation monitoring with serial human chorionic gonadotropin measurements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complete hydatidiform moles have a 15-20% risk of developing persistent gestational trophoblastic neoplasia, including choriocarcinoma.","Risk factors for persistent disease include human chorionic gonadotropin \u003E100,000 IU/L, large theca lutein cysts, and medical complications like hypertension.","Choriocarcinoma is a highly malignant form of gestational trophoblastic neoplasia that can develop after any pregnancy, but risk is highest after molar pregnancy."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Gestational Trophoblastic Disease (Green-top Guideline No. 38). London: RCOG; 2020 [cited 2024 Nov 24]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/gestational-trophoblastic-disease-green-top-guideline-no-38/","Ghassemzadeh S, Farci F, Kang M. Hydatidiform Mole. [Updated 2023 May 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459155/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50237"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16097"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50237"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T17:07:25+10:30",